what would be the junit meaning?

&gt; It&#39;s similar to how the word &quot;interface&quot; in some contexts refers to a 
&gt; generic OOP principle and in some other contexts refers to a specific 
&gt; Java language construct identified by a keyword.
&gt; 
&gt; Both JUnit assertions and Java assertions derive from the generic 
&gt; programming practice of making assertions in code as done with macros in 
&gt; C, but they are implemented differently; and they aren&#39;t the same thing.
&gt; 

I thought java used the assertion idea from Eiffel.

&gt;&gt; While testing we are almost always talking about assertion. I agree that using an Error, instead of 
&gt;&gt; an exception may be just a little wrong.
&gt;&gt; I am not sure what do you mean by &lt;&lt;right to the line that failed&gt;&gt;. Any Throwable will do just the 
&gt;&gt; same.
&gt; 
&gt; But where&#39;s the line that failed for a JUnit test? Suppose I have this 
&gt; method:
&gt; 
&gt;      public static void main(String[] args) {
&gt; 
&gt;          assert 2 == 3;
&gt;          System.out.println(&quot;Hello&quot;);
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt; Here&#39;s the stack trace:
&gt; 
&gt; Exception in thread &quot;main&quot; java.lang.AssertionError
&gt; 	at Test.main(Test.java:10)
&gt; 
&gt; Now let&#39;s change that method to use assertEquals instead:
&gt; 
&gt;      public static void main(String[] args) {
&gt; 
&gt;          junit.framework.Assert.assertEquals(2, 3);
&gt;          System.out.println(&quot;Hello&quot;);
&gt;      }
&gt; 
&gt; Here&#39;s the stack trace now:
&gt; 
&gt; Exception in thread &quot;main&quot; junit.framework.AssertionFailedError: 
&gt; expected:&lt;2&gt; but was:&lt;3&gt;
&gt; 	at junit.framework.Assert.fail(Assert.java:47)
&gt; 	at junit.framework.Assert.failNotEquals(Assert.java:282)
&gt; 	at junit.framework.Assert.assertEquals(Assert.java:64)
&gt; 	at junit.framework.Assert.assertEquals(Assert.java:201)
&gt; 	at junit.framework.Assert.assertEquals(Assert.java:207)
&gt; 	at Test.main(Test.java:10)
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; If I assertEquals(x, y), then the top line of the stack trace when the 
&gt; assertion fails is not assertEquals(). That will appear several lines 
&gt; down. The top of the stack trace will be the actual throw line in the 
&gt; Assert class. By contrast if I &quot;assert x == y&quot; and x is not equal to y, 
&gt; then that is the line that appears at the top of the stack trace.
&gt; 

